# Why Do More Men Commit Crimes Than Women? An In-Depth Analysis

## Introduction

The persistent observation that men commit more crimes than women is one of the most consistent findings in criminology. This gender disparity spans across cultures, historical periods, and crime categories, with men disproportionately represented among offenders, especially in violent and serious crimes. Understanding the underlying reasons for this phenomenon requires a multidisciplinary approach, encompassing biological, psychological, sociological, and criminological perspectives. This report aims to provide a comprehensive, evidence-based analysis of why more men commit crimes than women, integrating empirical data, theoretical frameworks, and critical evaluations of existing explanations.

## Overview of Gender Differences in Crime

### Statistical Evidence

- In Australia, only about 8% of prisoners are women, indicating a significant gender imbalance in incarceration rates ([Sarre et al., 2021](https://theconversation.com/men-are-more-likely-to-commit-violent-crimes-why-is-this-so-and-how-do-we-change-it-156400)).

- In the United States, men constitute approximately 73% of all arrests, 80.4% of arrests for violent crime, and 62.9% for property crime ([Federal Bureau of Investigation, 2011](https://ucr.fbi.gov/crime-in-the-u.s)).

- Globally, males account for about 95% of all convicted homicide perpetrators, and 78.7% of homicide victims are male ([United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime, 2013](https://www.unodc.org/unodc/en/data-and-analysis/statistics.html)).

- Women are more likely to be arrested for property crimes such as larceny-theft, fraud, and embezzlement, but men dominate in serious violent crimes including homicide, robbery, and sexual offenses ([Steffensmeier & Allan, 1996](https://www.annualreviews.org/doi/abs/10.1146/annurev.soc.22.1.459)).

| Crime Category          | Percentage of Male Offenders | Percentage of Female Offenders |
|------------------------|-----------------------------|-------------------------------|
| Homicide               | ~90%                        | ~10%                          |
| Violent Crime          | ~80%                        | ~20%                          |
| Property Crime         | ~60-70%                     | ~30-40%                       |
